1. Overview ¶

What is Python¶

Python is a free and open-source general programming language that was created in 1990 by Guido van Rossum. It is natively object-oriented, though strict OOP is practiced mostly in software engineering. Python is popular in fields related to data science and analytics thanks to some of its useful libraries (e.g., Numpy, Pandas).

Python facts¶

Python is...

  • interpreted, so it does not need to be compiled into machine language
  • interactive, allowing programs to be executed and debugged piece by piece
  • compatible with many platforms and languages
  • easy to read and maintain
  • high-level, abstracted from computer processes
  • minimalist in style, punctuation, and syntax
  • strict about indentation, indifferent about brackets and semicolons
  • fast (often if not always) - see the below figure showing log-likelihood computation times in a GARCH(1,1,) model for a dataset of length 10,000:

Setup¶

You need three things to set up Python:

  1. Download the Windows/Mac/Linux installer at python.org
  • Set up the PATH variable, which is a named string that points the OS to programs and executables stored on your computer and called when you run a Python program
  • Environment in which to start Python:
    • Command line
    • IDE (PyCharm, Spyder)
    • Interactive interpreter
